<DOC><DOCNO> AP890809-0094 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 1213EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u a PM-HighWinds 1stLd-Writethru a0521 08-09 0302</FIRST><SECOND>PM-High Winds, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0521,0305</SECOND><HEAD>High Winds Damage Dozens of Airplanes</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with at least 55 airplanes damaged;2 hangars demolished; PICKS UP 4th graf, `No injuries ...'</HEAD><DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A thunderstorm gusting to 99 mph destroyed ordamaged at least 55 planes at two airports and wrecked two hangars,causing more than $14 million in losses, authorities said today.   The storm Tuesday evening also knocked out power to 40,000 homesand businesses.   About 10 planes were heavily damaged, several were overturnedand one was blown about 200 feet at McCarran International Airport,spokesman Sam Ingalls said. Two corporate hangars were demolished,he said.   Damage was estimated at $14 million by Vicki Donaldson, anairport spokeswoman, although Ingalls cautioned that was an initialassessment.   At Sky Harbor Airport in nearby Henderson, 13 private planeswere destroyed and others damaged, spokeswoman Teddy Macknic said.Losses will run in the millions of dollars, she said.   No injuries were reported from the storm, which hit about 5:30p.m.   ``It was out of control,'' said Karen Kerr, who was working at atravel agency when the storm hit. ``The winds were blowing so hard.All of our phones and electricity was out for about three hours.''   The National Weather Service clocked winds up to 90 mph beforelightning knocked out electricity about 6 p.m. That was the highestwind speed recorded in the Las Vegas Valley, said Charlie Schlottof the weather service's airport office.   George Feick, supervisor of the Federal AviationAdministration's control tower at McCarran, said FAA equipmentregistered one gust at 99 mph.   By 10 p.m. power was restored to all but about 15,000 customersnear the airport and the University of Nevada-Las Vegas, said theLas Vegas Valley power company.</TEXT></DOC>